{"id":"math/0211420","submitter":"Michael Pinsker","authors":"Michael Pinsker","title":"Rosenberg's classification of maximal clones","comments":"Diploma Thesis written at the Vienna University of Technology under\n  the guidance of Prof. Martin Goldstern (2002)","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.LO","license":null,"abstract":"  We give a proof of I. G. Rosenberg's characterization of maximal clones. The\ntheorem lists six types of relations on a finite set such that a clone over\nthis set is maximal if and only if it contains just the functions preserving\none of the relations of the list. In Universal Algebra, this translates\nimmediately into a characterization of the finite preprimal algebras: A finite\nalgebra is preprimal if and only if its term operations are exactly the\nfunctions preserving a relation of one of the six types listed in the theorem.\nThe difficult part of the proof is to show that all maximal clones or preprimal\nalgebras respectively are of that form. This follows from, and, as we also\ndemonstrate, is indeed equivalent to, a characterization of primal algebras: We\nshow that the primal algebras are exactly those whose term operations do not\npreserve any of the relations on the list.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 26 Nov 2002 21:47:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
